ewspaper%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.thenational.scot%2Fnews%2F19803443.christmas-banned-scotland-four-centuries---changed%2F%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3EThe%20National%3C%2Fa%3E.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EBefore%20Christmas%20was%20reinstated%2C%20Scottish%20citizens%20turned%20to%20Hogmanay%20for%20festivities%20but%20the%20traditions%20that%20ensued%20are%20still%20popular%20to%20this%20day.%20For%20example%2C%20first%20footing%20traditionally%20involves%20bringing%20coal%20to%20someone's%20door%20for%20good%20luck%2C%20according%20to%20Scotland.org.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EWhile%20I've%20never%20brought%20anyone%20coal%2C%20I%20enjoy%20being%20the%20first%20person%20to%20visit%20a%20family%20or%20friend%20on%20January%201%20to%20wish%20them%20a%20happy%20new%20year.%20Growing%20up%2C%20it%20was%20typical%20for%20my%20family%20to%20%26quot%3Bfirst-foot%26quot%3B%20relatives%2C%20such%20as%20my%20grandparents.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Ch2%3EHogmanay%20in%20the%20present%20day%3C%2Fh2%3E%3Cp%3EA%20more%20recent%20tradition%20involves%20singing%20%26quot%3BAuld%20Lang%20Syne%2C%26quot%3B%20usually%20right%20after%20midnight%20on%20Hogmanay.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20song%20was%20penned%20by%20Scottish%20poet%20Robert%20Burns%20in%201788%20as%20a%20response%20to%20Scotland%20and%20England%20forming%20the%20UK%20in%201701%2C%20according%20to%20the%20tourism%20organization%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.visitscotland.com%2Finspiration%2Fculture%2Fauld-lang-syne%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3EVisit%20Scotland%3C%2Fa%3E.%20Burns%20included%20several%20traditional%20Scots%20phrases%20in%20the%20song%20to%20ensure%20Scotland's%20language%20and%20culture%20would%20be%20remembered.%20For%20example%2C%20the%20word%20%26quot%3Bjo%26quot%3B%20means%20%26quot%3Bdear%2C%26quot%3B%20and%20%26quot%3Bfiere%2C%26quot%3B%20translates%20to%20%26quot%3Bfriend%2C%26quot%3B%20the%20organization%20states.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThese%20days%2C%20the%20song%20is%20known%20all%20over%20the%20worl